07275nam a22015015i 9780691231518DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912315187 a10.1515/97806912315182doi  a(DE-B1597)626897  a(OCoLC)1323254620  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHF1359 7aPOL0620002bisacsh04a337223  aME 20502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122578:1 aQueralt, Didac, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPawned States :bState Building in the Era of International Finance /cDidac Queralt. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b45 b/w illus. 20 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Princeton Economic History of the Western World ;v10800tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 A Political Economy of External Finance -- tPART I. THE RISE OF GLOBAL FINANCE -- t3 The Globalization of Public Credit -- t4 Extreme Conditionality in International Lending -- t5 Debt Traps and Foreign Financial Control -- tPART II. THE CONSEQUENCES OF GLOBAL FINANCE FOR STATE BUILDING -- t6 War Finance -- t7 War, Credit, and Fiscal Capacity -- t8 Mechanisms of Persistence -- t9 State Building Trajectories -- t10 Conclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow foreign lending weakens emerging nationsIn the nineteenth century, many developing countries turned to the credit houses of Europe for sovereign loans to balance their books and weather major fiscal shocks such as war. This reliance on external public finance offered emerging nations endless opportunities to overcome barriers to growth, but it also enabled rulers to bypass critical stages in institution building and political development. Pawned States reveals how easy access to foreign lending at early stages of state building has led to chronic fiscal instability and weakened state capacity in the developing world.Drawing on a wealth of original data to document the rise of cheap overseas credit between 1816 and 1913, Didac Queralt shows how countries in the global periphery obtained these loans by agreeing to “extreme conditionality,” which empowered international investors to take control of local revenue sources in cases of default, and how foreclosure eroded a country’s tax base and caused lasting fiscal disequilibrium. Queralt goes on to combine quantitative analysis of tax performance between 1816 and 2005 with qualitative historical analysis in Latin America, Asia, Africa, and the Middle East, illustrating how overreliance on external capital by local leaders distorts their incentives to expand tax capacity, articulate power-sharing institutions, and strengthen bureaucratic apparatus.Panoramic in scope, Pawned States sheds needed light on how early and easy access to external finance pushes developing nations into trajectories characterized by fragile fiscal institutions and autocratic politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDebts, External. 0aDebts, Public. 0aInternational economic relations. 0aNation-building. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Geopolitics.2bisacsh  aAccountability.  aArms industry.  aAsset.  aBenefactor (law).  aBond (finance).  aBookkeeping.  aBureaucrat.  aCapital market.  aConditional probability.  aConditionality.  aCongress of Berlin.  aConsumption (economics).  aContract A.  aCountry.  aCredibility.  aCredit (finance).  aCredit rating.  aCreditor.  aDebasement.  aDebt.  aDebtor.  aDefault (finance).  aEconomic cost.  aEffectiveness.  aEndogeneity (econometrics).  aExpense.  aExternal deb